article.description:
Kara Lawson and Nicole Powell each scored 12
points to lead the Sacramento Monarchs to a 73-60 victory over the
Washington Mystics on Friday night.
article.headline: Monarchs pull away in fourth, win second in two nights
article.linkText: Monarchs pull away in fourth, win second in two nights
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- Kara Lawson has no problem coming off the
bench for the reigning WNBA champion Sacramento Monarchs.

Lawson scored 12 points in 19 minutes Friday to lead the
Sacramento Monarchs to a 73-60 victory over the Washington Mystics.

"That's the way it's been for four years," Lawson said. "It
doesn't matter whether you like it or not. You do whatever you're
supposed to do and obviously our system is successful.

"We won the championship last year so you do your role and you
do it to the best of your ability," added Lawson, a graduate of
nearby West Springfield (Va.) High. "That's our system and it's
great to play on a team where everyone has an opportunity to play.
That's what makes us a great team. Whether you start or come off
the bench you have a shot to play a lot if you play well."

Monarchs coach John Whisenant said that's the only way the
Monarchs could show their trademark defensive intensity.

"Defense wins championships," he said. "We won the WNBA last
year with being the only team, I'm told, in WNBA history that
didn't have a player that averaged 30 minutes a game. We had nine
players that averaged double-figure minutes. That's what we do and
that's what's required to play with our defensive intensity. It's
something that we live on."

Nicole Powell scored 12 points, DeMya Walker added 11, and Ticha
Penicheiro added season highs with nine rebounds and seven assists
as Sacramento (11-8) won its second in a row. Yolanda Griffith had
nine rebounds for the Monarchs.

Alana Beard led Washington (9-10) with 15 points, six rebounds
and three assists. She also committed seven of the Mystics' 23
turnovers.

Nikki Teasley had 12 points and Chasity Melvin added 10 points
and eight rebounds for the Mystics, who lost their second straight
at home after winning their first seven games of the season at
Verizon Center.

"We played the defending champions tonight and they played like
defending champions," Mystics coach Richie Adubato said. "They are
the best defensive team in the league and they are very hard to
score on. That's why they won the championship last year."

Lawson scored five points to spark the Monarchs on an 11-0 run
to take a 62-50 lead with 7:41 remaining.

"All of my high school coaches were here, a couple of my high
school teammates, and friends from high school that are still in
the area, so that's always special to me," Lawson said. "They've
seen me grow."

The Mystics got their first points of the fourth quarter when
Nakia Sanford converted a layup with 4:18 left.

Melvin scored six points as the Mystics closed the first half
with a 14-0 run for a 36-35 halftime lead.

The Monarchs, who led 33-19 midway through the second quarter,
failed to score during the final 3:54 before halftime.
